  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 3-9.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - 2. THE LINE OF JUDAH, TO HIS THREE GREAT-GRANDSONS. The line of Judah is, with a well-known object, the first to be taken up, although Judah stands fourth of Israel's sons. Judah has five sons: three, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Er, Onan, Shelah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", by a Canaanitess, the daughter of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Shad",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and two, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Pharez",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Zerah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", by ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Tamar",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", his own daughter-in-law, under the circumstances described (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 38:6-30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). There all these names are found in exact accord in the Authorized Version, in the Hebrew text, and in the Septuagint. The Septuagint Version, however (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 38:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), by an evident inaccuracy of translation, gives Shua as the name, not of the father, but of the daughter, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ῇ ὄνομα Σαυά",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Parallel passages are also found (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 46:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 26:19-22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Er and Onan died without issue, and the descendants of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Shelah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " are not mentioned till we reach ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 4:21-23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The line is now carried on by the twin sons of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Tamar",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (vers. 5, 6). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Pharez",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", with two sons, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Hezron",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Hamul",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 46:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ruth 4:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Zerah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", with five sons, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Zimri",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (or Zabdi, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 7:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Ethan, Heman, Calcol, Dara",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (or with many manuscripts, followed by the Targum, Syriac, and Arabic versions, Darda). If these last four names are not identical with those in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 4:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", they are not to be found in any available connection elsewhere, and the last two not at all. Upon this supposition, it is held by some that this very passage proves that the compiler drew on resources not possessed by us. The weight of evidence seems, however, largely in favour of the persons being the same. (See Gilbert Barrington's 'Old Testament Genealogies,' 1:206-208, well summarized in art. \"Darda,\" Smith's 'Bible Dictionary,' for as competent a discussion of the question as the present data will allow.) It needs to be constantly remembered that an enumeration like the above, of five so-called ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "sons",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", does not necessarily involve their being five ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "brothers",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", although in this case it looks the more as though they were so, as it is said ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "five of them in all",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " 1 Chronicles 2:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The sons of Judah and of Pharez, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 2:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".f. - The five sons of Judah are given according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 38",
        "children": []
